          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd Mr Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>London</placeName>
                                        <date>30 April 1851</date>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(4)">I duly received your favor of <date>31st</date>
                                        Ulto.<lb/> &amp; notice your observations in reply to my
                                        remarks on the arrangement<lb/> made for the Conciliator
                                        sent you, certainly I did not know of your having<lb/> paid
                                        duty freight &amp;c for except three copies sent through
                                                  <persName>Chapman</persName> the others<lb/> were
                                        forwarded by private hands, but nothing more need be said on
                                        that<lb/> subject as I accepted of your proposal &amp; which
                                        as I advised you <persName>Mrs. Joel</persName><lb/> settled
                                        for the <date>22 Jany</date>. Altho' as the author you may
                                        set a high value on your<lb/> Occident still you must
                                        remember that except for some good Sermons it is not
                                        inter<lb/>-esting to a European as the news in it from this
                                        part of the world is stale to them<lb/> &amp; any thing of
                                        congregational matters that happen in the
                                                  <placeName>West</placeName> is immediately
                                        inser<lb/>ted in the journals here &amp; appear long before
                                        the Occident is seen as to its nominal<lb/> value please to
                                        recollect when I sent you the Conciliator the price was 25/
                                        &amp; my<lb/> History is selling @12/ which together is
                                        equal to 5 vol. of the Occident it could be of<lb/> no use
                                        to me in my literary pursuits therefore it cannot be
                                        supposed I would lay out<lb/> money to purchase it. I have
                                        the first volume which my son in
                                                  <placeName>Jamaica</placeName> sent me &amp;<lb/>
                                        had you have presented me with the others should have been
                                        put to the <sic>expence</sic> of<lb/> having them bound
                                        which I now save, but as you make it a matter of dollars
                                        &amp; cents<lb/> I have no objection to treat it in the same
                                        way &amp; if you like it will give <persName>Mrs
                                                  Joel</persName> five<lb/>
                                        <hi rend="underline">unbound</hi> copies of the Conciliator
                                        for the 7 last volumes of your Occident on no other<lb/>
                                        terms would I add it to my already extensive library.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I thank you for your kind intention towards my
                                        recommendation of <persName>Mr Moraes</persName><lb/> who I
                                        feel convinced you will find grateful for any thing you may
                                        do for him &amp; equally<lb/> so that you will be pleased
                                        with him as you get better acquainted with him.<lb/> In
                                        reiterating towards yourself your kind expressions to me I
                                        remain</p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">Sincerely Yours</p>
                              <p rend="indent(4)">
                                        <persName role="author">E H Lindo</persName>
                              </p>
                              <p>I have just learned that <persName>Mr. M</persName> has been
                                        elected<lb/> &amp; to my great surprise that you were a
                                        candidate<lb/> for I had heard that you had refused the
                                        office</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd. Mr. I. Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                              </p>
